<PageLayout
  title="MC3R — the energy-partitioning receptor"
  kicker="Receptor · Melanocortin 3 receptor"
  description="MC4R's quieter sibling in the hypothalamus. Rather than switching appetite on and off, MC3R governs how the body spends its energy — and, it turns out, the timing of growth and puberty."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Melanocortin 3 receptor', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_3_receptor'] },
  ]}
>
  <ReceptorFacts receptor={receptor} />

  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'MC3R is MC4R’s hypothalamic sibling: rather than switching appetite on and off, it governs how the body partitions and spends energy.',
      'It also helps set the timing of growth and puberty, and contributes to sodium handling (natriuresis).',
      'It is activated by all the MSH peptides and ACTH, and antagonised by AgRP.',
      'Disruption shifts fat mass and feeding rhythm — a brake that complements MC4R rather than duplicating it.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    MC3R shares the hypothalamus with MC4R and responds to the same melanocortin
    peptides, yet it does a different job. For years it was the harder of the two
    central receptors to pin down — clearly involved in energy balance, but not in
    the simple "eat / don't eat" way of MC4R.<Cite n={1} /> Recent human genetics has
    given it a much sharper identity.
  </p>

  <h2>Energy partitioning, not just intake</h2>
  <p>
    Like the rest of the family, MC3R couples to Gs and cyclic AMP, and γ-MSH is a
    relatively potent agonist at this subtype while AgRP antagonises it.<Cite n={3} />
    But the phenotype of losing MC3R is distinctive: animal models point less to
    raw appetite and more to how energy is <em>partitioned</em> — the balance of
    fat versus lean mass and the efficiency with which food is used. MC3R also acts
    within the hypothalamic circuitry itself, modulating the POMC and AgRP neurons
    that feed into MC4R.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>The growth-and-puberty switch</h2>
  <p>
    The clearest picture of MC3R's purpose came in 2021. People carrying
    loss-of-function MC3R variants — including a rare individual with two defective
    copies — were found to have later puberty, reduced linear growth, lower lean
    mass, and lower circulating IGF-1; mice lacking Mc3r showed delayed sexual
    maturation and a reproductive cycle that no longer responded normally to
    nutritional state.<Cite n={2} /> The interpretation is elegant: the same
    nutrient-sensing melanocortin system bifurcates — signalling through MC4R to
    control how much energy is acquired, and through MC3R to decide how that energy
    is <em>spent</em> on growing up.<Cite n={2} />
  </p>

  <h2>Inflammation and the periphery</h2>
  <p>
    MC3R is not confined to the brain. It is expressed in the gut, heart, kidney,
    placenta, and on immune cells, where melanocortin signalling through MC3R is
    broadly anti-inflammatory and pro-resolving — part of why the receptor is
    studied as a target in inflammatory disease.<Cite n={1} /> For how MC3R sits
    alongside the other four receptors, see the
    <a href="/system">overview pillar</a>; for the appetite arm it complements, see
    <a href="/receptors/mc4r">MC4R</a>.
  </p>

  <p><a href="/receptors">← Back to all receptors</a></p>

  <References items={references} />
</PageLayout>
